{"type":"message","id":"b338219e","parentId":"88e68cd2","timestamp":"2026-04-03T19:26:54.813Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Não — **no modelo que fechámos, não**.\n\n## Resposta curta\n**Quem activa o `sm_s3_visual_planning` via CLI é o `w3_block2.py`, não o `b2_director`.**\n\n---\n\n# Separação correcta de papéis\n\n## `b2_director`\nÉ o **decisor macro**.\nEle:\n- lê bootstrap/resume\n- lê estado/checkpoints\n- decide a próxima transição\n- escreve estado\n- escreve checkpoints de intenção/progresso\n- termina\n\nExemplo:\n- escreve `s3_requested.json`\n\n## `w3_block2.py`\nÉ a **boundary executor / observer**\nEle:\n- observa checkpoints\n- quando vê `s3_requested.json`\n  - chama o `sm_s3_visual_planning` via CLI\n- quando vê `s3_completed.json`\n  - monta `b2.resume.v1`\n  - chama o `b2_director` via CLI outra vez\n\n## `sm_s3_visual_planning`\nÉ o **supervisor do sector**\nEle:\n- lê bootstrap do S3\n- gera activation plan\n- gera dispatch\n- chama os operators via CLI\n- valida outputs\n- compila\n- escreve checkpoint do sector + macro checkpoint do bloco\n\n---\n\n# Então onde entra a CLI?\n## CLI do `b2_director`\nÉ usada pelo:\n- `w3_block2.py`\n\n## CLI do `sm_s3_visual_planning`\nTambém é usada pelo:\n- `w3_block2.py`\n\n## CLI dos operators\nÉ usada pelo:\n- `sm_s3_visual_planning`\n\n---\n\n# Por que isso é importante\nPorque senão misturamos duas camadas:\n\n## se o director chamasse o supervisor directamente\nEle estaria a fazer:\n- decisão macro\n- e execução downstream imediata\n\nMas o modelo do B2 que consolidámos é mais limpo assim:\n- director decide\n- boundary observa checkpoint\n- boundary executa a activação seguinte\n\nIsso dá:\n- mais clareza\n- mais reentrância\n- melhor debug\n- melhor separação de responsabilidades\n\n---\n\n# Resposta directa\n## “e o diretor não é ele quem ativa o SM via CLI?”\n**Não no modelo actual.**\n\n### O correcto é:\n- `b2_director` escreve `s3_requested.json`\n- `w3_block2.py` detecta isso\n- `w3_block2.py` invoca o `sm_s3_visual_planning` via CLI\n\n---\n\n# O que eu corrigi agora então?\nA parte de `--session-id` do **supervisor -> operators** foi do lado do supervisor, porque esse hop sim pertence a ele.\n\n### Ou seja:\n- `w3_block2.py` → chama director e supervisor\n- `sm_s3_visual_planning` → chama operators\n\nCada camada endurecida no sítio certo.\n\nSe quiseres, eu também posso te escrever uma mini tabela “quem chama quem” pra colar no Claude Code e não deixar mais essa ambiguidade aparecer.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0e086492d0456bb30169d0147381d08191a3e755d809c89fa1\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":247,"output":637,"cacheRead":195712,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":196596,"cost":{"input":0.0006175000000000001,"output":0.009555000000000001,"cacheRead":0.048928,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0591005}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775244399937,"responseId":"resp_0e086492d0456bb30169d01470d9448191893599d2db8a2763"}}
{"type":"message","id":"f6d13a0b","parentId":"b338219e","timestamp":"2026-04-03T19:59:52.720Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Pre-compaction memory flush. Store durable memories only in memory/2026-04-03.md (create memory/ if needed). Treat workspace bootstrap/reference files such as MEMORY.md, SOUL.md, TOOLS.md, and AGENTS.md as read-only during this flush; never overwrite, replace, or edit them. If memory/2026-04-03.md already exists, APPEND new content only and do not overwrite existing entries. Do NOT create timestamped variant files (e.g., 2026-04-03-HHMM.md); always use the canonical 2026-04-03.md filename. If nothing to store, reply with NO_REPLY.\nCurrent time: Friday, April 3rd, 2026 — 16:59 (America/Sao_Paulo) / 2026-04-03 19:59 UTC"}],"timestamp":1775246392675}}
{"type":"message","id":"c6307e1d","parentId":"f6d13a0b","timestamp":"2026-04-03T20:00:11.766Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_M94iZTzAuuu2dPTJiLehaFiA|fc_0e086492d0456bb30169d01c3f677c8191b7de9e814deffdc3","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-04-03.md","content":"- B2/S3 runtime validation reached a decisive point: the correct primitive for `supervisor -> operator` in the current environment is **`exec -> openclaw agent --agent <operator_id> --message ... --json`**; ACP/sessions_spawn should not be treated as the central orchestration substrate for this path.\n- `b2_director` is now materially proven in runtime real for: (1) active bootstrap, (2) idempotent/no-op bootstrap, and (3) resume `s3_completed -> b2_completed` in `mode = s3_only`.\n- The correct B2 split is now explicit: `b2_director` is the macro decision-maker and writes checkpoints like `s3_requested.json`; `w3_block2.py` is the boundary observer/executor that detects those checkpoints and invokes `sm_s3_visual_planning`; the supervisor then invokes operators.\n- All 4 S3 operators were proved in real runs via the canonical CLI primitive. The key lessons were: `environment_location_extractor` and `symbolic_event_extractor` initially wrote legacy output shapes and had to be aligned to canonical `entities[]`-first schemas; `object_artifact_extractor` initially failed because dispatch generation was missing; `human_subject_extractor` was the first fully clean proof.\n- The first real external E2E-style Paperclip-side test exposed 3 last-mile production bugs in the supervisor path: (1) regression to ACP / subset execution, (2) failure to mirror `s3_completed.json` or `s3_failed.json` into `{b2_root}/checkpoints/`, and (3) path/encoding drift (`—` vs `-`) causing writes into the wrong directory tree. These are OpenClaw/supervisor-side bugs, not `w3_block2.py` bugs.\n- Supervisor hardening was applied in docs/instructions so that it should: (1) use CLI launch instead of ACP, (2) avoid silent subset execution, (3) write macro checkpoints into `{b2_root}/checkpoints/`, and (4) treat bootstrap paths as literal/canonical with no heuristic reconstruction.\n- A central postmortem and reusable gate now exist in `content_factory_block2/POSTMORTEM_AND_LEARNINGS_2026-04-03.md` and `content_factory_block2/SECTOR_PREFLIGHT_CHECKLIST.md`. These should be treated as mandatory references before opening any future sector (S4/S5/S6).\n- New production-hardening lesson: `openclaw agent --agent ...` reuses sessions by default, which will cause context/token buildup across videos. For production, fresh/isolated run behavior must be enforced instead of relying on default session reuse.\n- Recommended current workaround for clean context per run: use unique `--session-id` values per run/stage when invoking agents via CLI. Boundary-side (`w3_block2.py`) hardening was applied conceptually for director/supervisor stages, and the same principle must also hold for `sm_s3_visual_planning -> operators`.\n- Current go/no-go judgment for Perseus evolved during the day: after director + supervisor + operator-layer proofs, B2 became ready enough for a **narrow S3-only Paperclip/Perseus integration test**, but only as a checkpoint-driven, artifact-driven run — not as proof that the full block is production-hard yet.\n- Important communication/operational lesson: do not say “agent created” when only a folder/workspace exists. Only call an agent materialized when it appears in `openclaw agents list` and executes a real turn.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace\\\\memory\\\\2026-04-03.md\",\"content\":\"- B2/S3 runtime validation reached a decisive point: the correct primitive for `supervisor -> operator` in the current environment is **`exec -> openclaw agent --agent <operator_id> --message ... --json`**; ACP/sessions_spawn should not be treated as the central orchestration substrate for this path.\\n- `b2_director` is now materially proven in runtime real for: (1) active bootstrap, (2) idempotent/no-op bootstrap, and (3) resume `s3_completed -> b2_completed` in `mode = s3_only`.\\n- The correct B2 split is now explicit: `b2_director` is the macro decision-maker and writes checkpoints like `s3_requested.json`; `w3_block2.py` is the boundary observer/executor that detects those checkpoints and invokes `sm_s3_visual_planning`; the supervisor then invokes operators.\\n- All 4 S3 operators were proved in real runs via the canonical CLI primitive. The key lessons were: `environment_location_extractor` and `symbolic_event_extractor` initially wrote legacy output shapes and had to be aligned to canonical `entities[]`-first schemas; `object_artifact_extractor` initially failed because dispatch generation was missing; `human_subject_extractor` was the first fully clean proof.\\n- The first real external E2E-style Paperclip-side test exposed 3 last-mile production bugs in the supervisor path: (1) regression to ACP / subset execution, (2) failure to mirror `s3_completed.json` or `s3_failed.json` into `{b2_root}/checkpoints/`, and (3) path/encoding drift (`—` vs `-`) causing writes into the wrong directory tree. These are OpenClaw/supervisor-side bugs, not `w3_block2.py` bugs.\\n- Supervisor hardening was applied in docs/instructions so that it should: (1) use CLI launch instead of ACP, (2) avoid silent subset execution, (3) write macro checkpoints into `{b2_root}/checkpoints/`, and (4) treat bootstrap paths as literal/canonical with no heuristic reconstruction.\\n- A central postmortem and reusable gate now exist in `content_factory_block2/POSTMORTEM_AND_LEARNINGS_2026-04-03.md` and `content_factory_block2/SECTOR_PREFLIGHT_CHECKLIST.md`. These should be treated as mandatory references before opening any future sector (S4/S5/S6).\\n- New production-hardening lesson: `openclaw agent --agent ...` reuses sessions by default, which will cause context/token buildup across videos. For production, fresh/isolated run behavior must be enforced instead of relying on default session reuse.\\n- Recommended current workaround for clean context per run: use unique `--session-id` values per run/stage when invoking agents via CLI. Boundary-side (`w3_block2.py`) hardening was applied conceptually for director/supervisor stages, and the same principle must also hold for `sm_s3_visual_planning -> operators`.\\n- Current go/no-go judgment for Perseus evolved during the day: after director + supervisor + operator-layer proofs, B2 became ready enough for a **narrow S3-only Paperclip/Perseus integration test**, but only as a checkpoint-driven, artifact-driven run — not as proof that the full block is production-hard yet.\\n- Important communication/operational lesson: do not say “agent created” when only a folder/workspace exists. Only call an agent materialized when it appears in `openclaw agents list` and executes a real turn.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":174653,"output":801,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":175454,"cost":{"input":0.43663250000000003,"output":0.012015,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.44864750000000003}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775246392768,"responseId":"resp_0e086492d0456bb30169d01c39a79c8191a3c2ec9477ea87ea"}}
